# arvo-hash — Design

L2 hash-domain types and algorithm contracts. Ships a domain alias
over the arvo-bits opaque-bit container, plus generic trait contracts
for hash algorithms. No concrete algorithm implementations this
round; those land as trait implementors in follow-up rounds.

`#![no_std]`, no alloc. Depends on arvo-bits only.

## Why this crate exists

Hashes (content hashes, name hashes, pass-key identity) are numeric
algorithms on opaque bit-patterns. The stack needed one home for
the runtime carriers. arvo-bits provides the generic Bits container;
arvo-hash provides the domain vocabulary (ContentHash) and the algo
contracts (Hasher, HasherExt) consumers parameterise over.

Crate size is deliberately thin today. Growth surface (concrete
algorithms, cryptographic hashes as a sibling crate, semantic
aliases beyond ContentHash) is tracked in BACKLOG.

## Types

### ContentHash

A type alias for arvo-bits Bits<28>. Matches hilavitkutin-str's
low-28-bit FNV content-hash identity. Consumers that want a named
type at call sites (hilavitkutin-persistence StringTableEntry,
clause resolver pass-key identity) bind ContentHash instead of
the raw Bits<28>.

```rust
pub type ContentHash = arvo_bits::Bits<28>;
```

A direct type alias rather than a newtype: the semantic domain is
fully captured by the bit width; no additional invariants warrant
a distinct type.

## Algorithm contracts

### Hasher (canonical, streaming)

```rust
pub trait Hasher<const N: u8> {
    fn update(&mut self, bytes: &[u8]);
    fn finalize(self) -> arvo_bits::Bits<N>;
}
```

Streaming hash: feed bytes incrementally, finalise to an N-bit
opaque pattern. Consumers implementing a hash algorithm implement
this trait.

### HasherExt (oneshot convenience, blanket impl)

```rust
pub trait HasherExt<const N: u8>: Hasher<N> + Sized {
    /// One-shot: update with the complete input, then finalize.
    fn hash(mut self, bytes: &[u8]) -> arvo_bits::Bits<N> {
        self.update(bytes);
        self.finalize()
    }
}
impl<H: Hasher<N>, const N: u8> HasherExt<N> for H {}
```

HasherExt's default method provides oneshot ergonomics over any
Hasher implementor. The blanket impl means every Hasher automatically
exposes a .hash(bytes) one-shot form; implementors do not write
their own oneshot path. Mirrors the round-202604201048 Encoder /
Decoder + EncoderExt / DecoderExt pattern: streaming is canonical,
oneshot is a derived convenience.

## Usage

Downstream code parameterises over the trait; swapping algorithm
is a type-parameter change, not a call-site rewrite.

Streaming:

```rust
fn intern_chunks<H: Hasher<28>>(mut hasher: H, chunks: &[&[u8]]) -> ContentHash {
    for chunk in chunks { hasher.update(chunk); }
    hasher.finalize()
}
```

One-shot:

```rust
fn intern<H: HasherExt<28>>(hasher: H, bytes: &[u8]) -> ContentHash {
    hasher.hash(bytes)
}
```

To swap algorithm, change the type the caller supplies. No site
edits; the trait signatures stay put.

## Dependencies

- arvo-bits (L1): provides Bits<const N: u8> (the underlying
  container) plus BitWidth / BitAccess trait bounds.

arvo-hash does not depend on arvo L0 directly. Future algorithm
modules may bring in arvo deps as needed; ship-time scope keeps
the dep surface minimal.

## What this crate does NOT contain

- Concrete hash algorithms (FNV, xxHash, CRC32); follow-up rounds.
- Cryptographic hashes (SHA, BLAKE); out of scope entirely.
  A sibling arvo-crypto crate covers cryptographic needs if they
  surface.
- Semantic aliases beyond ContentHash; consumers that need
  NameHash, KeyHash, or similar start with their own local alias
  over ContentHash or Bits<N> and promote to arvo-hash once
  patterns stabilise.
- rkyv Archive impls; consumers define Archive at their boundary.
- Owned byte buffers; all hashing takes &[u8] input.

## Design rule

`#![no_std]`, no alloc. Algorithm-agnostic: the crate defines the
contract, not the implementation. Consumer code parameterises over
the trait; concrete algorithms ship as implementors in follow-up
rounds.

